    <h3 class="title"><a href="/node/349#comment-1264" class="active">Many Languages, One Programmer</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="http://www.tallent.us/" rel="nofollow">Richard Tallent</a> (not verified) on Mon, 2006-02-06 20:08.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>I agree, I had a very similar idea a few years ago:</p>
<p><a href="http://www.tallent.us/blog/commentview.aspx?guid=a44c5fbf-d78e-4ebd-ad45-addc763d1fed" title="http://www.tallent.us/blog/commentview.aspx?guid=a44c5fbf-d78e-4ebd-ad45-addc763d1fed">http://www.tallent.us/blog/commentview.aspx?guid=a44c5fbf-d78e-4ebd-ad45...</a></p>
<p>.NET's common runtime and its new "partial classes" feature are certainly an improvement, but context-switching between languages on the fly is still a dream for now.</p>
